04471nam a22006015i 9781787449299DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874492997 a10.1515/97817874492992doi  a(DE-B1597)674923  a(OCoLC)1227044291  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPS3552.O874b.T437 2021 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813.54223  aHU 31842rvk0(DE-625)rvk/53886:1 aTharaud, Barry Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaul Bowles :bIn the American Grain /cBarry Charles Tharaud.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 1bCamden House, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (234 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in American Literature and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Paul Bowles as a Canonical Writer -- t1: Paul Bowles on Intercultural Understanding: Too Far from Home -- t2: The Discovery of Existence: Without Stopping -- t3: Emersonian Shadows -- t4: Culture and Existence in Bowles’ Short Fiction -- t5: Gide and Bowles in North Africa: The Sheltering Sky -- t6: Language, Noise, Silence: Self and Society in Let It Come Down -- t7: The Spider’s House: The Social Construction of Reality -- t8: Existence and Imagination: Up Above the World -- t9: The Letters: In Touch -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShows that the writings of Paul Bowles, who is often seen as a literary renegade, owe much to the antinomian American tradition of Emerson and his literary descendants.Paul Bowles has often been considered a cult writer, a literary renegade: he lived more than fifty years as an expatriate in Morocco, and according to Norman Mailer, his works "let in the murder, the drugs, the incest, the call ofthe orgy, the end of civilization." In recent decades Bowles has found greater acceptance as a serious writer, as evidenced by the two-volume, 2,000-page Library of America edition of his works published in 2002. Still, he has rarely if ever been seen as having written in the antinomian tradition of Emerson and his literary descendants. The present book makes the case for doing so by demonstrating basic Emersonian attitudes and objectives in Bowles' lifeand works, especially in his focus on human consciousness and perception and on the need for the individual to escape from the trammels of social and cultural conditioning. Bowles' intellectual pursuits seem to have developed at first from his own spontaneous attitudes, which were then reinforced by his conservative and individualistic New England background on both sides of his family and deepened by a serious study of anthropology, Emersonian transcendentalism, and related "Oriental" thought such as the theosophy of Krishnamurti. Despite his half century in Tangier, Bowles is a writer who is thoroughly "in the American grain."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aPaul Bowles.  aantinomian tradition.  ahuman consciousness.  aliterary renegade.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787449299?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787449299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787449299/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles